Abstract

Typing of lambda-terms in Elementary and Light Affine Logic (EAL , LAL  resp.) has been studied for two different reasons: on the one hand the evaluation of typed terms using LAL  (EAL  resp.) proof-nets admits a guaranteed polynomial (elementary, resp.) bound; on the other hand these terms can also be evaluated by optimal reduction using the abstract version of Lamping’s algorithm. The first reduction is global while the second one is local and asynchronous. We prove that for LAL  (EAL  resp.) typed terms, Lamping’s abstract algorithm also admits a polynomial (elementary, resp.) bound. We also show its soundness and completeness (for EAL  and LAL  with type fixpoints), by using a simple geometry of interaction model (context semantics).

1 Introduction

Background and Motivations.

Light logics such as Light Affine Logic (LAL) and Elementary Affine Logic (EAL) have been introduced in [18, 4] and then studied as type systems for lambda-calculus [3, 11, 12, 6, 9, 10] and semantically (e.g. in [24, 27, 13]). Their analysis has been motivated by two distinct features:

  • 1.

    Complexity-certified reduction: using the syntax of proof-nets, the logics LAL  (EAL, respectively) ensure that the program terminates with a polynomial (elementary, respectively) time bound;

  • 2.

    Simple optimal reduction: for lambda-terms typed in these systems one can use the abstract version of Lamping’s algorithm [23], without the so-called oracle, so plain graph rewriting with local rules.

However each of these approaches has its drawbacks:

  • •

    Proof-net reduction is global, requires the handling of boxes, and thereby enforces a form of synchronicity which is awkward to implement;

  • •

    Optimal reduction is local, asynchronous – and elegant, but …does not offer any guaranteed complexity bound.

Actually, even the fact that the abstract Lamping algorithm is correct for terms of EAL and LAL is not completely straightforward: it was pointed out since [4] and is part of the folklore, but it seems no explicit direct proof of this statement is available in the literature, although the general techniques of [21] could be applied to this restricted setting.

The goal of this paper is therefore to bring together the best of these two worlds: we prove that terms typable in LAL (EAL, respectively) can be reduced by the Lamping abstract algorithm with a certified polynomial (elementary, respectively) time bound. Moreover a type derivation in LAL or EAL carries two kinds of information: the sharing information and the boxing information. We actually show here that the boxing information is not needed to perform Lamping’s abstract algorithm. Some systems like DLAL [9] or restrictions of EAL [11] do not use sharing: in that case knowing that the term is typeable (without knowing the type) is sufficient to apply the abstract algorithm.

Actually the bounds of light logics can also be obtained without the proof-net machinery, in plain lambda-calculus, if one considers fragments of the type systems, possibly with restricted (lazy) reduction [9, 10]. However this is still a global form of reduction (β𝛽\beta-reduction). Here we aim to handle the full type systems and to switch to a local reduction, which is motivating for concrete implementations and in particular for distributed evaluation [28].

Optimal Reduction and Light Logics.

The fact that EAL typable terms can be reduced with Lamping’s abstract algorithm is quite remarkable, since it is known that the bookkeeping needed for the oracle causes inefficiencies in optimal reduction [25].

On the other hand, proof-net reduction in these systems is performed with guaranteed complexity bound, one might think that the preservation of bounds when switching from proof-net reduction to optimal reduction is a consequence of optimality itself. However this is actually not true: the optimality concerns the number of parallel beta-steps, which is not directly related to the normalisation time [2, 1]. For an in-depth study of optimal reduction one can consult [5].

Moreover, techniques used when analyzing proof-net (or lambda-term) reduction time cannot be directly applied here. In particular, the level-by-level reduction strategy (see [18, 3]) has no counterpart in the framework of sharing graphs, where copying is done incrementally.

Contributions.

Our main results are:

  • •

    We define a general class of admissible translations from light logics type derivations to sharing graphs, subsuming the ones proposed before.

  • •

    For each admissible translation, we show that graph reduction is sound and complete with respect to lambda-reduction.

  • •

    Moreover, we show that graph reduction can be performed in bounded time, where the bound is of the same complexity order as the one we have on the underlying logical system.

Moreover we believe that the main technique used to prove the complexity bounds (Section 6), based on the definition of weights for sharing graphs (or interaction nets, [22]) following [14] is of its own interest and could presumably be applied to other problems.

2 Soundness and Completeness in the General Case

Before introducing the specific logical systems we are interested in, we define the notions of soundness and completeness for abstract systems of graph reduction. Throughout the paper, ΛΛ\Lambda is the set of pure, untyped, lambda terms. If A𝐴A is a set and →→\rightarrow is a binary relation on A𝐴A, the set of normal forms in A𝐴A (with respect to →→\rightarrow) will be denoted 𝑁𝐹​(A)→𝑁𝐹subscript𝐴→\mathit{NF}(A)_{\rightarrow}.

Definition 1 (Graph Rewriting Systems)

A ΘΘ\Theta-graph rewriting system is a quintuple (Θ,Δ,→Δ,𝒯,ℛ)ΘΔsubscript→Δ𝒯ℛ(\Theta,\Delta,\rightarrow_{\Delta},\mathcal{T},\mathcal{R}) where:

  • •

    Θ⊆ΛΘΛ\Theta\subseteq\Lambda is a set of lambda-terms to which the technique can be applied.

  • •

    ΔΔ\Delta is a set of graphs.

  • •

    →Δsubscript→Δ\rightarrow_{\Delta} is a rewriting relation on ΔΔ\Delta.

  • •

    𝒯𝒯\mathcal{T} is a total binary relation from ΘΘ\Theta to ΔΔ\Delta, called the initial translation.

  • •

    ℛℛ\mathcal{R} is a function from ΔΔ\Delta to ΛΛ\Lambda, called the readback.

Note that 𝒯𝒯\mathcal{T} is a relation and not a mere function, since we want to allow several possible translations of a term (this is related to the fact that we will allow the possibility to decorate a given lambda-term as several different proof-nets).

Definition 2 (Soundness)

We say that the ΘΘ\Theta-graph rewriting system (Θ,Δ,→Δ,𝒯,ℛ)ΘΔsubscript→Δ𝒯ℛ(\Theta,\Delta,\rightarrow_{\Delta},\mathcal{T},\mathcal{R}) is sound with respect to a reduction relation →→\rightarrow on ΛΛ\Lambda iff for every term t∈Θ𝑡Θt\in\Theta, if G∈𝒯​(t)𝐺𝒯𝑡G\in\mathcal{T}(t) and G𝐺G reduces to normal form H𝐻H (in →Δsubscript→Δ\rightarrow_{\Delta}) then t𝑡t reduces to normal form u𝑢u (in →→\rightarrow) and ℛ​(H)=uℛ𝐻𝑢\mathcal{R}(H)=u:

Soundness of a ΘΘ\Theta-graph rewriting system implies that if we start with a term t𝑡t in ΘΘ\Theta, translate it into a graph, reduce the graph and finally read-back a term u𝑢u, then u𝑢u is the normal form of t𝑡t. This does not mean the ΘΘ\Theta-graph rewriting system will necessarily do its job: to be sure about that, we need completeness:

Definition 3 (Completeness)

We say that the ΘΘ\Theta-graph rewriting system (Θ,Δ,→Δ,𝒯,ℛ)ΘΔsubscript→Δ𝒯ℛ(\Theta,\Delta,\rightarrow_{\Delta},\mathcal{T},\mathcal{R}) is complete with respect to a reduction relation →→\rightarrow on ΛΛ\Lambda iff for every term t∈Θ𝑡Θt\in\Theta if t𝑡t reduces to normal form u𝑢u, then any G∈𝒯​(t)𝐺𝒯𝑡G\in\mathcal{T}(t) reduces to normal form H𝐻H, where ℛ​(H)=uℛ𝐻𝑢\mathcal{R}(H)=u.

3 Type Assignment Systems and Proof-Nets

Formulae of (intuitionistic) elementary affine logic (EAL for short) are generated by the following productions:

A::=α|A⊸A|!A|∀α.A|μα.AA::=\alpha\;|\;A\multimap A\;|\;!A\;|\;\forall\alpha.A\;|\;\mu\alpha.A

where α𝛼\alpha ranges over a countable set of atoms. Recall that !! is called an exponential connective or modality.

Here we are considering in fact EAL with type fixpoints (recursive types) but this does not modify its normalisation properties [15]. Most references in the literature deal with the second order fragment EAL∀subscriptEALfor-all\textsf{EAL}_{\forall}, which does not include type fixpoints.

EAL can be seen as a type system for terms in ΛΛ\Lambda: Figure 1 presents type assignment by means of sequent calculus, which is tedious for typing but convenient for studying the dynamics. Other presentations of typing can be found in the literature [11, 12, 7]. Note that sharing is allowed, for instance by using rules X𝑋X and U𝑈U. Θ𝖤𝖠𝖫subscriptΘ𝖤𝖠𝖫\Theta_{\mathsf{EAL}} denotes the set of lambda terms which are typable in elementary affine logic.

Elementary affine logic proofs can be formulated as a system of (intuitionistic) proof-nets Δ𝖤𝖠𝖫subscriptΔ𝖤𝖠𝖫\Delta_{\mathsf{EAL}}, defined inductively on Figure 2. Node X𝑋X is called a contraction node. The principal edge of a node v𝑣v is the edge incident to v𝑣v through its principal port (indicated with a ∙∙\bullet). A cut is an edge e={v,w}𝑒𝑣𝑤e=\{v,w\} which is principal for both v𝑣v and w𝑤w.

EAL proof-nets can be endowed with a rewriting relation →𝖤𝖠𝖫subscript→𝖤𝖠𝖫\rightarrow_{\mathsf{EAL}} (see Figure 3). The important case of →𝖤𝖠𝖫subscript→𝖤𝖠𝖫\rightarrow_{\mathsf{EAL}} is when an X𝑋X node meets a R!subscript𝑅R_{!} node, corresponding to a box: in this case the box is duplicated and the doors L!subscript𝐿L_{!} of the two copies are linked to X𝑋X nodes (contraction normalisation step).

If v𝑣v (resp. e𝑒e) is a node (resp. edge) of a proof-net, ∂(v)𝑣\partial(v) (resp. ∂(e)𝑒\partial(e)) denotes its box-depth (level). If G∈Δ𝖤𝖠𝖫𝐺subscriptΔ𝖤𝖠𝖫G\in\Delta_{\mathsf{EAL}} is a proof-net, its depth ∂(G)𝐺\partial(G) is the maximal depth of its edges. The stratification property of EAL states that the depth ∂(e)𝑒\partial(e) of an edge does not change through →𝖤𝖠𝖫subscript→𝖤𝖠𝖫\rightarrow_{\mathsf{EAL}}.

Light Affine Logic.

LAL can be obtained from EAL by adopting a stricter exponential discipline: one restricts the rule P!subscript𝑃P_{!} of EAL to the case where ΓΓ\Gamma contains at most one formula, but also adds a new connective §§\S with rule P§subscript𝑃§P_{\S} (see Figure 4). The connective §§\S is a weak form of !!, that does not allow for contraction (rule X𝑋X).

There is a translation (.)e(.)^{e} from LAL to EAL formulae obtained by replacing §§\S with !!. It extends to a translation on proofs.Therefore the set Θ𝖫𝖠𝖫subscriptΘ𝖫𝖠𝖫\Theta_{\mathsf{LAL}} of lambda-terms typable in LAL is included in Θ𝖤𝖠𝖫subscriptΘ𝖤𝖠𝖫\Theta_{\mathsf{EAL}}.

The proofs-nets of LAL are defined as those of EAL  but with two new nodes L§subscript𝐿§L_{\S} and R§subscript𝑅§R_{\S} and conditions on boxes: a box with R!subscript𝑅R_{!} main door (!!-box) can have at most one L!subscript𝐿L_{!} door; a box with R§subscript𝑅§R_{\S} main door (§§\S-box) can have any number of L§subscript𝐿§L_{\S} and L!subscript𝐿L_{!} doors. A rewriting relation →𝖫𝖠𝖫subscript→𝖫𝖠𝖫\rightarrow_{\mathsf{LAL}} is defined on these proof-nets [14]. This reduction does not cause any duplication of a §§\S-box.

The translation (.)e(.)^{e} can be extended naturally to a translation from LAL to EAL proof-nets, and it maps →𝖫𝖠𝖫subscript→𝖫𝖠𝖫\rightarrow_{\mathsf{LAL}} to →𝖤𝖠𝖫subscript→𝖤𝖠𝖫\rightarrow_{\mathsf{EAL}}. Therefore the set of LAL proof-nets can be seen as a subset of Δ𝖤𝖠𝖫subscriptΔ𝖤𝖠𝖫\Delta_{\mathsf{EAL}}. Hence properties of EAL proof-nets will be valid in particular for LAL proof-nets and we will state them only for EAL (except for complexity issues in Section 6).

Paths.

A direct path is a sequence of edges e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} such that the following conditions hold:

  • •

    For every 1≤i<n1𝑖𝑛1\leq i<n, eisubscript𝑒𝑖e_{i} and ei+1subscript𝑒𝑖1e_{i+1} have a vertex visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i} in common;

  • •

    For every 1≤i<n1𝑖𝑛1\leq i<n, ei≠ei+1subscript𝑒𝑖subscript𝑒𝑖1e_{i}\neq e_{i+1} and either eisubscript𝑒𝑖e_{i} or ei+1subscript𝑒𝑖1e_{i+1} is principal for visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}.

An example of a direct path is reported in Figure 5(a). We say that a direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} with n≥2𝑛2n\geq 2 starts at v𝑣v iff e1={v,w}subscript𝑒1𝑣𝑤e_{1}=\{v,w\} is principal for v𝑣v and there is z𝑧z with e2={w,z}subscript𝑒2𝑤𝑧e_{2}=\{w,z\}. A direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} is simple iff for every 1≤i<n1𝑖𝑛1\leq i<n, the edge ei+1subscript𝑒𝑖1e_{i+1} is principal for visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}. The direct path in Figure 5(b) is simple, while the one in Figure 5(a) is not. A direct path is maximal iff it is not part of any longer direct path.

Two edges e,g𝑒𝑔e,g are non-consecutive iff there cannot be any direct path in the form e,g𝑒𝑔e,g (or, equivalently, in the form g,e𝑔𝑒g,e). A box b𝑏b in a proof-net N𝑁N is special iff any direct path starting from one of its premises is simple.

Lemma 1

Any non-simple direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} starting at any node v𝑣v contains a cut eisubscript𝑒𝑖e_{i} such that ∂(ei)≤∂(e1)subscript𝑒𝑖subscript𝑒1\partial(e_{i})\leq\partial(e_{1}).

  • Proof.

    As a preliminary fact, take notice that for any simple direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n}, it holds that ∂(en)≤∂(e1)subscript𝑒𝑛subscript𝑒1\partial(e_{n})\leq\partial(e_{1}). Indeed, you can enter a box only through a principal port. We can prove the lemma by induction on n𝑛n:

    • •

      If n=1𝑛1n=1, then the path is simple.

    • •

      Then, observe that any non-simple, direct path e1,e2subscript𝑒1subscript𝑒2e_{1},e_{2} starting in v𝑣v contains a cut, namely e1subscript𝑒1e_{1}. Indeed, by definition e1subscript𝑒1e_{1} is principal for v𝑣v and, since the path is non-simple, e1subscript𝑒1e_{1} is principal for v1subscript𝑣1v_{1}, too.

    • •

      Let n≥3𝑛3n\geq 3 and e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} be a non-simple direct path starting from v𝑣v. If e1,…,en−1subscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛1e_{1},\ldots,e_{n-1} is non-simple, then by inductive hypothesis, it contains a cut. If e1,…,en−1subscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛1e_{1},\ldots,e_{n-1} is simple and e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} is not simple, then en−1subscript𝑒𝑛1e_{n-1} is principal for vn−2subscript𝑣𝑛2v_{n-2} and vn−1subscript𝑣𝑛1v_{n-1}. As a consequence, en−1subscript𝑒𝑛1e_{n-1} is a cut. Moreover, ∂(en−1)≤∂(e1)subscript𝑒𝑛1subscript𝑒1\partial(e_{n-1})\leq\partial(e_{1}).

    This concludes the proof. □□\Box

Strategies.

There are two reduction strategies for proof-nets in Δ𝖤𝖠𝖫subscriptΔ𝖤𝖠𝖫\Delta_{\mathsf{EAL}} (or Δ𝖫𝖠𝖫subscriptΔ𝖫𝖠𝖫\Delta_{\mathsf{LAL}}) that are of particular interest for our purposes:

  • •

    The level-by-level strategy, LBL. A cut at level n+1𝑛1n+1 cannot be reduced if there are cuts at level n𝑛n.

  • •

    The modified level-by-level strategy, MLBL. It is the level-by-level one with an additional constraint: whenever we copy a box b𝑏b, b𝑏b must be a special box.

Notice that MLBL is a reduction strategy due to Lemma 1. Indeed, if a box b𝑏b is involved in a cut e𝑒e but is not special, then we can find another cut g𝑔g such that ∂(g)≤∂(e)𝑔𝑒\partial(g)\leq\partial(e). But g𝑔g could be itself an exponential cut involving a non-special box. This sequence of non-special boxes must however be finite, because otherwise we would have a cycle that cannot appear in any proof-net (correctness criterion)..

Complexity Bounds.

We can now recall the main results on EAL and LAL :

Theorem 1 (Girard [18])

For every natural number n𝑛n, there is a polynomial (respectively, elementary function) en:ℕ→ℕ:subscript𝑒𝑛→ℕℕe_{n}:\mathbb{N}\rightarrow\mathbb{N} such that for every proof-net N𝑁N of LAL (respectively, EAL ) if N→nMsuperscript→𝑛𝑁𝑀N\rightarrow^{n}M in the MLBL strategy, then n≤e∂(N)​(|N|)𝑛subscript𝑒𝑁𝑁n\leq e_{\partial(N)}(|N|) and |M|≤e∂(N)​(|N|)𝑀subscript𝑒𝑁𝑁|M|\leq e_{\partial(N)}(|N|).

Recall that binary lists can be represented in LAL with the type: W=∀α.!(α⊸α)⊸!(α⊸α)⊸§(α⊸α)W=\forall\alpha.!(\alpha\multimap\alpha)\multimap!(\alpha\multimap\alpha)\multimap\S(\alpha\multimap\alpha). This way, a term of LAL type t:W⊸§k​W:𝑡⊸𝑊superscript§𝑘𝑊t:W\multimap\S^{k}W can be converted to a proof-net, and its application to a list evaluated in polynomial time using →𝖫𝖠𝖫subscript→𝖫𝖠𝖫\rightarrow_{\mathsf{LAL}}. However this is still a global evaluation procedure and we want to replace it by optimal reduction.

4 Lamping’s Abstract Algorithm

Now we turn to the local reduction procedure. The set of abstract sharing graphs Δ𝖠𝖲𝖱subscriptΔ𝖠𝖲𝖱\Delta_{\mathsf{ASR}} is given by the nodes of Figure 6: the 3rd node is called fan and is given together with an integer index i𝑖i.

A rewriting relation →𝖠𝖲𝖱subscript→𝖠𝖲𝖱\rightarrow_{\mathsf{ASR}} on Δ𝖠𝖲𝖱subscriptΔ𝖠𝖲𝖱\Delta_{\mathsf{ASR}} is defined on Figure 7. Notice that we omit the garbage collection rules. This omission is anyway harmless: the readback procedure (Section 7.2) is not affected by the presence of garbage and the complexity of garbage collection is linear in the size of the graph.

If G𝐺G is a sharing graph, 𝑓𝑝​(G)𝑓𝑝𝐺\mathit{fp}(G) is the set of its free ports (dangling edges), while 𝑤𝑝​(G)𝑤𝑝𝐺\mathit{wp}(G) is the set of edges which are incident to ⊗tensor-product\otimes-nodes. If u𝑢u is a node of G𝐺G, then 𝑝𝑝​(u)𝑝𝑝𝑢\mathit{pp}(u) is the principal port of u𝑢u.

To translate proof-nets into sharing graphs we will turn contraction nodes into fans. However we need to choose the indices for the fans. For that, any proof-net N𝑁N is given together with a labelling function ℱℱ\mathcal{F} from the set of its contraction nodes to natural numbers. The translation 𝒯𝖠𝖲𝖱𝖤𝖠𝖫subscriptsuperscript𝒯𝖤𝖠𝖫𝖠𝖲𝖱\mathcal{T}^{\mathsf{EAL}}_{\mathsf{ASR}} from proof-nets to abstract sharing graphs will be defined up to such labelling functions. 𝒯𝖠𝖲𝖱𝖤𝖠𝖫​(N,ℱ)subscriptsuperscript𝒯𝖤𝖠𝖫𝖠𝖲𝖱𝑁ℱ\mathcal{T}^{\mathsf{EAL}}_{\mathsf{ASR}}(N,\mathcal{F}) is the graph G∈Δ𝖠𝖲𝖱𝐺subscriptΔ𝖠𝖲𝖱G\in\Delta_{\mathsf{ASR}} obtained in the following way:

  • •

    Replace nodes R⊸subscript𝑅⊸R_{\multimap} (resp. L⊸subscript𝐿⊸L_{\multimap}) by nodes λ𝜆\lambda (resp. @@@),

  • •

    Remove boxes and nodes L!subscript𝐿L_{!}, R!subscript𝑅R_{!}, L∀subscript𝐿for-allL_{\forall}, R∀subscript𝑅for-allR_{\forall}, Lμsubscript𝐿𝜇L_{\mu}, Rμsubscript𝑅𝜇R_{\mu},

  • •

    Replace each contraction node v𝑣v with a fan-in with index ℱ​(v)ℱ𝑣\mathcal{F}(v).

We denote by |ℱ|ℱ|\mathcal{F}| the cardinality of the image of the labelling function ℱℱ\mathcal{F}.

We say a labelling function ℱℱ\mathcal{F} for the proof-net N𝑁N is compatible with depths iff ℱ​(v)=ℱ​(w)ℱ𝑣ℱ𝑤\mathcal{F}(v)=\mathcal{F}(w) implies ∂(v)=∂(w)𝑣𝑤\partial(v)=\partial(w). From now on we will consider only labelling functions which are compatible with depths. Note that in a proof-net reduction step N→𝖤𝖠𝖫Msubscript→𝖤𝖠𝖫𝑁𝑀N\rightarrow_{\mathsf{EAL}}M, each node of M𝑀M comes from a unique node of N𝑁N; a labelling function ℱℱ\mathcal{F} for N𝑁N then induces in a natural way a labelling function for M𝑀M, that we will also write ℱℱ\mathcal{F}. By the stratification property of EAL, if ℱℱ\mathcal{F} is compatible with depths for N𝑁N, then so it is for M𝑀M.

In previous works on light logics and optimal reduction, two particular translations of proof-nets have been considered:

  • •

    The level translation, LT: the labelling function ℱℱ\mathcal{F} is the one defined by the depths, that is ℱ​(v)=∂(v)ℱ𝑣𝑣\mathcal{F}(v)=\partial(v).

  • •

    The distinct labelling translation, DLT: the labelling function ℱℱ\mathcal{F} is the discrete one (each contraction node has a different index),

Observe that the second translation offers the advantage of simplicity, since it does not need the information provided by boxes in N𝑁N. The first translation, on the other hand, has the advantage that it minimizes the number of indices used to annotate fans in the abstract sharing graph. We will show that these two translations, as well as any one based on a labelling compatible with depths, is sound and complete for beta-reduction. For this purpose we will use as tool a specific context semantics. We give on Fig.8(a) an abstract sharing graph that will serve as running example. It is obtained as the DLT of a proof-net corresponding to a derivation of f:!(A⊸A)⊸!(A⊸A)⊸B,g:!(A⊸A)⊢u:Bf:!(A\multimap A)\multimap!(A\multimap A)\multimap B,g:!(A\multimap A)\vdash u:B, where u=(λx.fxx)(λz.gz)u=(\lambda x.f\;x\;x)(\lambda z.g\;z). In Fig. 8(b) we give its normal form for →𝖠𝖲𝖱subscript→𝖠𝖲𝖱\rightarrow_{\mathsf{ASR}}.

The concepts of principal port, direct path, simple path, etc. can be easily transferred from proof-nets to sharing graphs. The number of maximal paths in a cut-free sharing graph is bounded:

Lemma 2

Let G𝐺G be a cut-free sharing graph and let e𝑒e be one of its free ports. Then there are at most |G|+1𝐺1|G|+1 maximal direct paths in the form e=e1,…,en𝑒subscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e=e_{1},\ldots,e_{n}.

  • Proof.

    Consider any such maximal direct path e=e1,…,en𝑒subscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e=e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} and the corresponding sequence of nodes v1,…,vn−1subscript𝑣1…subscript𝑣𝑛1v_{1},\ldots,v_{n-1}. Since there are no cuts in G𝐺G, there cannot be any eisubscript𝑒𝑖e_{i} which is principal for both vi−1subscript𝑣𝑖1v_{i-1} and visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i}. This implies e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} has a very constrained structure: there is 1≤j≤n1𝑗𝑛1\leq j\leq n such that:

    • •

      eisubscript𝑒𝑖e_{i} is principal for visubscript𝑣𝑖v_{i} whenever 1≤i<j1𝑖𝑗1\leq i<j.

    • •

      ejsubscript𝑒𝑗e_{j} is not principal for vj−1subscript𝑣𝑗1v_{j-1} (if j>1𝑗1j>1) nor for vjsubscript𝑣𝑗v_{j} (if j<n𝑗𝑛j<n).

    • •

      eisubscript𝑒𝑖e_{i} is principal for vi−1subscript𝑣𝑖1v_{i-1} whenever j<i≤n𝑗𝑖𝑛j<i\leq n

    So, each such path can be divided into three parts. Now, the third part of the path, namely ej+1,…,ensubscript𝑒𝑗1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{j+1},\ldots,e_{n}, is completely determined by the first two parts, namely e1,…,ejsubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑗e_{1},\ldots,e_{j}. But since e1subscript𝑒1e_{1} is always equal to e𝑒e, there are at most |G|+1𝐺1|G|+1 paths in this form, because every binary tree with n𝑛n nodes has at most n+1𝑛1n+1 leaves. This concludes the proof. □□\Box

Now we want to bound the complexity of this rewriting procedure and show that it is sound and complete.

5 Context Semantics

5.1 Interpretation of Proof-Nets and Sharing Graphs

Context semantics will be the tool for showing soundness of sharing graph reduction (following [20]). A context can be seen as a token carrying a piece of information and travelling around the net [17]. As we are considering a more constrained setting than [20, 19, 16] the contexts can be presented as tuples, as in [8]. This reflects the stratified structure of EAL  proof-nets.

Definition 4 (Elementary contexts)

An elementary context C𝐶C of length k𝑘k is a tuple of stacks S1,…,Sk,Tsubscript𝑆1…subscript𝑆𝑘𝑇S_{1},\ldots,S_{k},T over the alphabet {𝗉,𝗊}𝗉𝗊\{\mathsf{p},\mathsf{q}\}. Stacks Sisubscript𝑆𝑖S_{i} are called exponential stacks, stack T𝑇T is called multiplicative stack. ε𝜀\varepsilon denotes the empty stack, x​S𝑥𝑆xS denotes the stack obtained by pushing x𝑥x on S𝑆S and S​T𝑆𝑇ST denotes the concatenation of stacks S𝑆S and T𝑇T. The partial order ⊑square-image-of-or-equals\sqsubseteq on stacks is the prefix order. We also denote by ⊑square-image-of-or-equals\sqsubseteq the pointwise order on the product of stacks. Finally ⊑msubscriptsquare-image-of-or-equals𝑚\sqsubseteq_{m} will denote the order on elementary contexts defined by identity on the exponential stacks Sisubscript𝑆𝑖S_{i} (1≤i≤k1𝑖𝑘1\leq i\leq k) and ⊑square-image-of-or-equals\sqsubseteq on the multiplicative stack T𝑇T.

Definition 5 (Valid paths)

Let N𝑁N be in Δ𝖤𝖠𝖫subscriptΔ𝖤𝖠𝖫\Delta_{\mathsf{EAL}} and ℱℱ\mathcal{F} a labelling function, with k=|ℱ|𝑘ℱk=|\mathcal{F}|.

  • •

    A context of N𝑁N relative to ℱℱ\mathcal{F} is a pair (p,C)𝑝𝐶(p,C) where p𝑝p is an edge of N𝑁N and C𝐶C is an elementary context of length k+1𝑘1k+1.

  • •

    The binary relation ∼similar-to\sim on contexts is defined by symmetrically closing the rules in Table 1 and adding for the other (binary) nodes the rule acting as identity on the elementary context (no rule for the W𝑊W node).

  • •

    A direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} in N𝑁N is valid with respect to two elementary contexts C1subscript𝐶1C_{1} and Cnsubscript𝐶𝑛C_{n} iff the nodes along the path transform the context (e1,C1)subscript𝑒1subscript𝐶1(e_{1},C_{1}) into (en,Cn)subscript𝑒𝑛subscript𝐶𝑛(e_{n},C_{n}). More precisely, there must be elementary contexts C2,…,Cn−1subscript𝐶2…subscript𝐶𝑛1C_{2},\ldots,C_{n-1} such that (ei,Ci)∼(ei+1,Ci+1)similar-tosubscript𝑒𝑖subscript𝐶𝑖subscript𝑒𝑖1subscript𝐶𝑖1(e_{i},C_{i})\sim(e_{i+1},C_{i+1}) whenever 1≤i<n1𝑖𝑛1\leq i<n. Definition 6 (Context semantics)

Given a proof-net N𝑁N of EAL  and a labelling function ℱℱ\mathcal{F}, the context semantics ⟦N⟧ℱ\llbracket N\rrbracket_{\mathcal{F}} of N𝑁N is the set of pairs ((e,C),(f,D))𝑒𝐶𝑓𝐷((e,C),(f,D)) such that e𝑒e and f𝑓f are conclusion edges of N𝑁N and (e,C)▷(f,D)▷𝑒𝐶𝑓𝐷(e,C)\triangleright(f,D).

To simplify the notation we will sometimes omit the ℱℱ\mathcal{F} and write ⟦N⟧delimited-⟦⟧𝑁\llbracket N\rrbracket instead of ⟦N⟧ℱ\llbracket N\rrbracket_{\mathcal{F}}. Notice that as the transitions are deterministic (see Table 1) and as when reaching a conclusion no transition is possible anymore, if (e,C)▷(f,D)▷𝑒𝐶𝑓𝐷(e,C)\triangleright(f,D) and (e,C)▷(g,E)▷𝑒𝐶𝑔𝐸(e,C)\triangleright(g,E) are both in ⟦N⟧ℱ\llbracket N\rrbracket_{\mathcal{F}} then f=g𝑓𝑔f=g and D=E𝐷𝐸D=E. Therefore the context semantics of N𝑁N can be seen as a (partial) function on contexts. Notice, however, that there can be two essentially different reasons why the context semantics is undefined on (e,C)𝑒𝐶(e,C):

  • •

    There could be finitely many valid paths starting in e𝑒e which are all valid with respect to C𝐶C and some context D𝐷D, but none of them ends in a conclusion.

  • •

    There are arbitrary long valid paths starting in e𝑒e which are all valid with respect to C𝐶C and some context D𝐷D; this means there is not any context (g,E)𝑔𝐸(g,E) such that g𝑔g is a conclusion edge and (e,C)▷(g,E)▷𝑒𝐶𝑔𝐸(e,C)\triangleright(g,E).

However we will see in Section 5.3 that this second possibility is guaranteed never to occur for proof-nets.

Given a sharing graph G𝐺G and a partition ℱℱ\mathcal{F} of its fan nodes, its contexts and context semantics ⟦G⟧delimited-⟦⟧𝐺\llbracket G\rrbracket are defined similarly to that of proof-nets (Table 2). It is then clear that the context semantics is preserved by the translation from proof-nets to sharing graphs:

5.2 Reduction and Context Semantics

Now we consider the behaviour of the context semantics with respect to the reduction of proof-nets and sharing graphs. Let us start with the latter case, which is easier.

Take a look at the rewriting rules for sharing graph. If we focus on the edges involved, we can observe that:

  • •

    The annihilation rewriting steps erase one edge, namely the cut. The other four edges involved have residuals which are defined in the usual way. The edges which are not directly involved in the rewriting have trivially defined residuals. No edge is created.

  • •

    The copying rewriting steps erases one edge but creates another four edges, which are called the edges created in the rewriting step. The cut in the redex has no residual.

Let G𝐺G be a sharing graph and let E𝐸E be a subset of the edges of G𝐺G. The direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} in G𝐺G is said to be long enough for E𝐸E iff e1,en∉Esubscript𝑒1subscript𝑒𝑛𝐸e_{1},e_{n}\notin E.

Lemma 4 (Preservation of Long-Enough Paths)

Suppose G𝐺G is a sharing graph, G→𝖠𝖲𝖱Hsubscript→𝖠𝖲𝖱𝐺𝐻G\rightarrow_{\mathsf{ASR}}H by firing a cut e𝑒e. Then:

  • •

    If a direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} in G𝐺G is long enough for {e}𝑒\{e\} and valid for C𝐶C and D𝐷D, then there is a direct path g1,…,gmsubscript𝑔1…subscript𝑔𝑚g_{1},\ldots,g_{m} in H𝐻H valid for C𝐶C and D𝐷D such that g1subscript𝑔1g_{1} is the residual of e1subscript𝑒1e_{1} and gmsubscript𝑔𝑚g_{m} is the residual of ensubscript𝑒𝑛e_{n}.

  • •

    If a direct path g1,…,gmsubscript𝑔1…subscript𝑔𝑚g_{1},\ldots,g_{m} in H𝐻H is long enough for the set of edges created in the rewriting step and valid for C𝐶C and D𝐷D, then there is a direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} in G𝐺G valid for C𝐶C and D𝐷D such that g1subscript𝑔1g_{1} is the residual of e1subscript𝑒1e_{1} and gmsubscript𝑔𝑚g_{m} is the residual of ensubscript𝑒𝑛e_{n}

  • Proof.

    Consider the rules of Figure 7 and observe that in each case of rewriting step the context semantics partial function of the subgraph concerned is unchanged. □□\Box

Proposition 3

Let G𝐺G be a sharing graph and G→𝖠𝖲𝖱Hsubscript→𝖠𝖲𝖱𝐺𝐻G\rightarrow_{\mathsf{ASR}}H then ⟦G⟧=⟦H⟧\llbracket G\rrbracket=\llbracket H\rrbracket.

  • Proof.

    Just observe that any conclusion-to-conclusion valid path in G𝐺G is long enough for any cut, while any conclusion-to-conclusion valid path in H𝐻H is long enough for the set of edges created in the rewriting step. The thesis follows easily from Lemma 4. □□\Box

As to proof-nets the situation is more delicate. It is well-known that geometry of interaction or context semantics are usually not preserved by general proof-net reduction [19, 16, 26]. To deal with this problem we define a partial order ≼precedes-or-equals\preccurlyeq on context functions. Context semantics will be preserved up to ≽succeeds-or-equals\succcurlyeq but that will be sufficient to obtain a soundness result with respect to lambda-calculus.

Definition 7

Let f𝑓f, g𝑔g be two partial functions on contexts. Then f≼gprecedes-or-equals𝑓𝑔f\preccurlyeq g iff for any context p,C𝑝𝐶p,C we have:

  • 1.

    If f​(p,C)𝑓𝑝𝐶f(p,C) is defined, then so is g​(p,C)𝑔𝑝𝐶g(p,C), and g​(p,C)=f​(p,C)𝑔𝑝𝐶𝑓𝑝𝐶g(p,C)=f(p,C),

  • 2.

    If f​(p,C)𝑓𝑝𝐶f(p,C) is undefined then either:

    • i.

      g​(p,C)𝑔𝑝𝐶g(p,C) is undefined,

    • ii.

      or f​(p,D)𝑓𝑝𝐷f(p,D) is undefined whenever D⊒mCsubscriptsquare-original-of-or-equals𝑚𝐷𝐶D\sqsupseteq_{m}C.

The point in subcase 2.ii is that f​(p,C)𝑓𝑝𝐶f(p,C) is undefined, but it is not merely because of a lack of information in the multiplicative stack, since no increase of information on this stack can trigger an answer. The behaviour of f𝑓f on such input is in fact irrelevant for the read-back process that we will define, so the definition of ≼precedes-or-equals\preccurlyeq does not require anything on g​(p,C)𝑔𝑝𝐶g(p,C) in this case.

Lemma 5

The relation ≼precedes-or-equals\preccurlyeq is a partial order.

  • Proof.

    The non-obvious fact is whether this relation is transitive. Assume we have f≼gprecedes-or-equals𝑓𝑔f\preccurlyeq g and g≼hprecedes-or-equals𝑔ℎg\preccurlyeq h. Given a context (p,C)𝑝𝐶(p,C) and a stack T0subscript𝑇0T_{0} we will denote by (p,C)::T0(p,C)::T_{0} the context obtained from p,C𝑝𝐶p,C by replacing the multiplicative stack T𝑇T of C𝐶C by T​T0𝑇subscript𝑇0TT_{0}.

    Take a context (p,C)𝑝𝐶(p,C): if f​(p,C)𝑓𝑝𝐶f(p,C) is defined, then so are g​(p,C)𝑔𝑝𝐶g(p,C) and h​(p,C)ℎ𝑝𝐶h(p,C), and we have h​(p,C)=f​(p,C)ℎ𝑝𝐶𝑓𝑝𝐶h(p,C)=f(p,C). Otherwise if f​(p,C)𝑓𝑝𝐶f(p,C) is undefined we have 2 subcases to consider. First, if for any stack T0subscript𝑇0T_{0}, f((p,C)::T0)f((p,C)::T_{0}) is undefined, then the condition is fulfilled. Otherwise there exists a T0subscript𝑇0T_{0} such that f((p,C)::T0)f((p,C)::T_{0}) is defined, and g​(p,C)𝑔𝑝𝐶g(p,C) is undefined; then g((p,C)::T0)g((p,C)::T_{0}) is defined. As g≼hprecedes-or-equals𝑔ℎg\preccurlyeq h we deduce that h​(p,C)ℎ𝑝𝐶h(p,C) is undefined and the condition is fulfilled. Therefore f≼hprecedes-or-equals𝑓ℎf\preccurlyeq h. □□\Box

Now we can state the property of context semantics w.r.t. proof-net reduction:

5.3 Acyclicity

We now describe properties of valid paths in the proof-nets and sharing graphs we are dealing with.

Proposition 5 (Finiteness of valid paths for proof-nets)

  • Proof.

    This is proved in [8] for EAL∀subscriptEALfor-all\textsf{EAL}_{\forall}, and the proof can be easily adapted to EAL  using the fact that EAL is strongly normalising. □□\Box

A cycle is a direct path e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} such that:

  • •

    e1=ensubscript𝑒1subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1}=e_{n};

  • •

    n≥2𝑛2n\geq 2;

  • •

    e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} is valid with respect to C=C0,…,Ck,T𝐶subscript𝐶0…subscript𝐶𝑘𝑇C=C_{0},\ldots,C_{k},T and D=D0,…,Dk,S𝐷subscript𝐷0…subscript𝐷𝑘𝑆D=D_{0},\ldots,D_{k},S;

  • •

    For every 0≤i≤k0𝑖𝑘0\leq i\leq k, either Ci⊑Disquare-image-of-or-equalssubscript𝐶𝑖subscript𝐷𝑖C_{i}\sqsubseteq D_{i} or Di⊑Cisquare-image-of-or-equalssubscript𝐷𝑖subscript𝐶𝑖D_{i}\sqsubseteq C_{i};

    Either T⊑Ssquare-image-of-or-equals𝑇𝑆T\sqsubseteq S or S⊑Tsquare-image-of-or-equals𝑆𝑇S\sqsubseteq T.

Proposition 6 (Acyclicity of Proof-Nets)

If N𝑁N is a proof-net, then its context semantics does not contain any cycle.

  • Proof.

    Indeed if the proof-net N𝑁N contained a cycle, then by repeatedly composing it with itself one would get valid paths of arbitrary length, which would contradict Proposition 5. □□\Box

Proposition 7

Let N𝑁N be an EAL  proof-net, G=𝒯𝖠𝖲𝖱𝖤𝖠𝖫​(N,ℱ)𝐺subscriptsuperscript𝒯𝖤𝖠𝖫𝖠𝖲𝖱𝑁ℱG=\mathcal{T}^{\mathsf{EAL}}_{\mathsf{ASR}}(N,\mathcal{F}) and G→𝖠𝖲𝖱∗Hsuperscriptsubscript→𝖠𝖲𝖱𝐺𝐻G\rightarrow_{\mathsf{ASR}}^{*}H . 6 Complexity

We study the complexity of sharing graph reduction by defining a weight WGsubscript𝑊𝐺W_{G} for any sharing graph G𝐺G. The underlying idea is the following: the weight of G𝐺G is the sum of the individual weight of each u∈VG𝑢subscript𝑉𝐺u\in V_{G}, the latter being the number of possible copies of u𝑢u that are produced during normalisation. We will relate the weight to the number of reduction steps of the sharing graph, and then, for sharing graphs coming from EAL(and LAL), bound the weight by using the properties of proof-nets.

Formally, the weight of an edge u𝑢u will be defined as the number of different valid paths e1,…,ensubscript𝑒1…subscript𝑒𝑛e_{1},\ldots,e_{n} satisfying certain additional constraints. First of all, e1subscript𝑒1e_{1} must be 𝑝𝑝​(u)𝑝𝑝𝑢\mathit{pp}(u). Secondly, ensubscript𝑒𝑛e_{n} must be:

  • •

    Either the principal edge of a node v𝑣v such that 𝑡𝑦​(u)=𝑡𝑦​(v)𝑡𝑦𝑢𝑡𝑦𝑣\mathit{ty}(u)=\mathit{ty}(v).

  • •

    Or an edge in 𝑓𝑝​(G)∪𝑤𝑝​(G)𝑓𝑝𝐺𝑤𝑝𝐺\mathit{fp}(G)\cup\mathit{wp}(G).

This way the weight of u𝑢u will be exactly the number of copies of u𝑢u that will eventually appear during reduction of G𝐺G. This can be characterized by context semantics exploiting Proposition 2:

Definition 8 (Weight)

    WG=∑u∈VG(|Bu−|+|Pu−|+|Eu−|−1).subscript𝑊𝐺subscript𝑢subscript𝑉𝐺superscriptsubscript𝐵𝑢subscriptsuperscript𝑃𝑢subscriptsuperscript𝐸𝑢1W_{G}=\sum_{u\in V_{G}}(|B_{u}^{-}|+|P^{-}_{u}|+|E^{-}_{u}|-1).

7 Soundness

Suppose we are in the following situation:

In words, we translated a typable term t𝑡t to a sharing graph G𝐺G, then normalised G𝐺G to H𝐻H. We now need to define a read-back procedure ℛℛ\mathcal{R} that extracts the normal form u𝑢u of t𝑡t from H𝐻H. We have to design a variant of the readback procedures in the literature, e.g. [20, 26], since here we are not handling a generic encoding of terms into proof-nets but an encoding based on type derivations.

The procedure ℛΛ𝖠𝖲𝖱subscriptsuperscriptℛ𝖠𝖲𝖱Λ\mathcal{R}^{\mathsf{ASR}}_{\Lambda} is defined on sharing graphs, but does not look at the internal structure of the graph itself; rather, the procedure is defined as a set of queries to the underlying context semantics. To prove ℛΛ𝖠𝖲𝖱subscriptsuperscriptℛ𝖠𝖲𝖱Λ\mathcal{R}^{\mathsf{ASR}}_{\Lambda} is correct, we will show that whenever π:Γ⊢u:A:𝜋Γproves𝑢:𝐴\pi:\Gamma\vdash u:A is a cut-free type derivation, ℛΛ𝖠𝖲𝖱subscriptsuperscriptℛ𝖠𝖲𝖱Λ\mathcal{R}^{\mathsf{ASR}}_{\Lambda} applied to the proof-net M𝑀M induced by π𝜋\pi returns u𝑢u. This is enough to prove soundness. Indeed, the context semantics of M𝑀M is essentially the same as the one of H𝐻H:

Observe that we could even apply the readback procedure to G𝐺G, without reducing G𝐺G to its normal form H𝐻H. This, however, would make the read-back process less efficient, as the whole computation would be done by the context semantics.

9 Conclusions

We proved that Lamping’s abstract algorithm is sound and complete for beta reduction of EAL (and LAL) typable pure lambda-terms. Moreover, the number of graph interaction steps is shown to be bounded by the same kind of bounds holding for proof-net normalisation. All these results have been established by exploiting context semantics. In particular, complexity results have been inferred in an innovative way, being inspired by [14].

Further work includes the extension of the approach to general optimal reduction. In the full algorithm, however, relative bounds should take the place of absolute bounds, since any pure lambda term can be reduced.
